WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.644
Pulmonary embolism is a life-threatening
condition where a blood clot,

2
00:00:04.005 --> 00:00:06.704
usually from a deep vein thrombosis in the
legs, travels

3
00:00:06.704 --> 00:00:09.704
to the pulmonary arteries and blocks blood
flow to part of the lung.

4
00:00:10.225 --> 00:00:12.744
This creates a critical
ventilation-perfusion mismatch.

5
00:00:13.324 --> 00:00:16.284
Ventilation may be normal, but perfusion
is reduced or absent,

6
00:00:16.944 --> 00:00:19.625
resulting in dead space ventilation and
impaired gas exchange.

7
00:00:19.985 --> 00:00:22.745
From an RT perspective, the key is
recognizing the pattern.

8
00:00:23.465 --> 00:00:26.305
Patients often present with sudden-onset
dyspnea, tachycardia,

9
00:00:26.444 --> 00:00:27.684
and unexplained hypoxemia.

10
00:00:27.684 --> 00:00:30.225
You may also see tachycardia, chest pain,

11
00:00:30.325 --> 00:00:32.784
especially pleuritic, and sometimes
hemoptysis.

12
00:00:33.444 --> 00:00:35.485
Breath sounds can be normal, which is a
major clue.

13
00:00:35.944 --> 00:00:38.325
If a patient is hypoxic but lungs sound
clear, you

14
00:00:38.325 --> 00:00:40.305
should immediately think about pulmonary
embolism.

15
00:00:41.244 --> 00:00:44.365
Pathophysiologically, the clot increases
pulmonary vascular resistance,

16
00:00:44.525 --> 00:00:45.924
which can strain the right ventricle.

17
00:00:46.305 --> 00:00:48.604
As pressure builds, right heart failure
can develop,

18
00:00:48.985 --> 00:00:51.224
reducing cardiac output and worsening
oxygen delivery.

19
00:00:51.465 --> 00:00:55.904
This is why large or massive PEs can
rapidly become hemodynamically unstable.

20
00:00:56.764 --> 00:00:58.845
Diagnostics often begin with clinical
suspicion.

21
00:00:59.365 --> 00:01:03.744
You may see a low PaO2 and lower normal
PaCO2 early due to hyperventilation.

22
00:01:04.504 --> 00:01:07.224
D-dimer can support the possibility of
clot formation, but

23
00:01:07.224 --> 00:01:10.305
CT pulmonary andiography is the gold
standard for diagnosis.

24
00:01:10.864 --> 00:01:14.105
Ventilation-perfusion scans may also be
used when CT is contraindicated.

25
00:01:14.525 --> 00:01:15.845
Management depends on severity.

26
00:01:16.644 --> 00:01:18.745
Oxygen is used to treat hypoxemia, but
remember,

27
00:01:19.105 --> 00:01:21.305
it does not fix the underlying perfusion
problem.

28
00:01:21.925 --> 00:01:25.105
Anticryoglation is the cornerstone of
treatment to prevent further clot formation.

29
00:01:25.425 --> 00:01:27.925
In more severe cases, thrombolytics may be
used to break

30
00:01:27.925 --> 00:01:29.985
down the clot, and in extreme situations,

31
00:01:30.504 --> 00:01:32.985
surgical or catheter-based interventions
may be required.

32
00:01:33.625 --> 00:01:37.404
Red flags you must recognize include
sudden hypotension, signs of

33
00:01:37.404 --> 00:01:39.264
shock, altered mental status, or worsening

34
00:01:39.264 --> 00:01:41.464
hypoxemia despite oxygen therapy.

35
00:01:41.644 --> 00:01:45.544
These suggest a massive PE and require
immediate escalation.

36
00:01:45.964 --> 00:01:48.144
As a respiratory therapist, your role is
critical.

37
00:01:48.625 --> 00:01:51.385
You assess oxygenation, monitor for signs
of right heart strain,

38
00:01:51.864 --> 00:01:55.165
evaluate ABG trends, and recognize when a
patient is deteriorating.

39
00:01:55.705 --> 00:01:58.845
You are often the first to identify that
something doesn't fit the typical respiratory

40
00:01:58.845 --> 00:01:59.245
pattern.

41
00:01:59.925 --> 00:02:01.345
For board prep, remember this.

42
00:02:01.985 --> 00:02:04.824
Pulmonary embolism is a perfusion problem,
not a ventilation problem.

43
00:02:05.425 --> 00:02:08.184
Think sudden dyspnea, clear lungs,
hypoxemia,

44
00:02:08.645 --> 00:02:10.985
and risk factors like immobility or recent
surgery.

45
00:02:11.684 --> 00:02:13.425
Early recognition can save a life.

